---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Mermaid Uncovered — The Disney Deception — Nazaryah"
  description="Atargatis, Dagon, and the fish-goddess worship Yahuah condemned — traced from Syria to Disney's box office."
>
  <div class="sw-wrap">

    <!-- ── HERO ── -->
    <section class="sw-hero">
      <a href="/disney" class="sw-back">&#8592; The Disney Deception</a>
      <p class="sw-label">&#8213; The Disney Deception &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="sw-title">The Mermaid Uncovered</h1>
      <p class="sw-sub">
        Atargatis, Dagon, and the fish-goddess worship Yahuah condemned
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── MODE BAR ── -->
    <div class="sw-mode-bar">
      <button id="btn-quick" class="sw-mode-btn sw-mode-active" data-tip="Fits between bath time and bedtime.">&#9654; Quick Read</button>
      <span class="sw-mode-divider">&#8213;</span>
      <button id="btn-full" class="sw-mode-btn" data-tip="This is why they invented coffee.">Full Study</button>
    </div>

    <!-- ── QUICK READ PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-quick">

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-kicker">The mermaid is one of the oldest documented idols on earth — and most parents have no idea she's in their living room.</p>
          <p>Long before Disney, half-woman half-fish goddesses were worshipped across the ancient world with blood sacrifice, temple prostitution, and fertility rituals. This is the 90-second version of her story.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Where She Actually Came From</p>
          <p>The oldest known mermaid is Atargatis — the chief goddess of northern Syria, worshipped from at least 1000 BC. Her temple at Hierapolis kept sacred fish in a pool, and temple prostitution and child sacrifice were part of her worship. This is the goddess Disney turned into a redheaded teenager named Ariel.</p>
          <p>Her Babylonian cousin is Oannes, the fish-man whose priests wore fish-head mitres — the same mitre the Pope wears today. Her medieval descendant is Melusine, the twin-tailed mermaid at the center of the Starbucks logo. The lineage is unbroken.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Exodus 20:4–5</p>
            <p>"Thou shalt not make unto thee any graven image, or any likeness of any thing... <strong>that is in the water under the earth</strong>: thou shalt not bow down thyself to them, nor serve them..."</p>
          </div>
          <p>Yahuah named the exact category the mermaid belongs to. This was not vague. It was surgical.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What the Movie Actually Does</p>
          <p>The 1989 film preserves every element of the myth that matters to the worship system:</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li><strong>Ariel rebels against her father</strong> — the fertility cult's feminine defiance of patriarchal order, intact.</li>
            <li><strong>Ariel trades her voice through a sea-witch's spell</strong> — transformation through witchcraft, explicitly forbidden in Exodus 22:18 and Deuteronomy 18:10–12.</li>
            <li><strong>Ariel seeks a prince</strong> — the fertility-cult marriage narrative: the goddess-figure seeks the sun-consort, the union that produces the harvest.</li>
            <li><strong>The climax features a trident, storm, and ritual transformation</strong> — all drawn from sea-deity worship.</li>
            <li><strong>Starbucks carries the same goddess</strong> — the twin-tailed Melusine, halo-ringed, on every cup. The same idol, different packaging.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The film is not neutral. It is a fertility myth with a pop soundtrack, teaching children that defying their fathers and pursuing romantic love through witchcraft are noble impulses.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">So Now What?</p>
          <p>You don't have to throw the VHS in the fire tonight. But the next time it comes on, sit down and ask your daughters — do you know where Ariel came from before Hans Christian Andersen? Ask them why Yahuah included "things in the water under the earth" in the second commandment. Those questions do more than any ban.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; 1 John 5:21</p>
            <p>"Little children, keep yourselves from idols. Amen."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-footer-quote">
        <div class="sw-summary-block">
          <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; The Short Version</p>
          <p class="sw-summary-text">The mermaid is Atargatis — a Syrian fish-goddess from 1000 BC — and Ariel is her newest face. The second commandment named her category specifically. Disney just gave her red hair.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="sw-cta-link" style="text-align:center; margin-top:1.5rem;">
          <button id="btn-full-cta" class="sw-mode-btn" style="font-size:0.75rem; letter-spacing:2px;">&#8594; Read the Full Study</button>
        </p>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-quick -->

    <!-- ── FULL STUDY PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-full" style="display:none">

    <!-- ── INTRO ── -->
    <section class="sw-section">
      <div class="sw-prose">
        <p class="sw-kicker">The mermaid is not a fairy tale. She is one of the oldest documented idols on earth — and Disney's version is not a harmless modernization. It is a continuation of the same worship system Scripture explicitly forbids.</p>
        <p>
          Long before Hans Christian Andersen picked up a pen and centuries before Disney turned her red hair into merchandise, half-woman half-fish goddesses were worshipped across the ancient world with blood sacrifice, temple prostitution, and fertility rituals. The Little Mermaid came from Syria, from Babylon, from Philistia — the very nations Yahuah commanded Israel to destroy.
        </p>
        <p>
          This study walks the mermaid back to her origin and shows why Disney's version is not a harmless modernization but a continuation of the same worship system Scripture explicitly forbids.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── ATARGATIS ── -->
    <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
      <div class="sw-prose">
        <p class="sw-section-heading">The Original Mermaid: Atargatis</p>
        <p>
          The oldest known mermaid in recorded history is Atargatis (also called Derketo), the chief goddess of northern Syria. Her worship is documented from at least 1000 BC, and her primary temple stood in Hierapolis-Bambyce. She was the great fertility goddess — the giver of life through water — depicted as a woman from the waist up and a fish from the waist down.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Greek writer Lucian of Samosata described her temple in detail. Sacred fish were kept in a pool at her sanctuary, and it was considered death to touch or eat them. Temple prostitution was part of her worship, and once a year the men of the city had their heads shaved and offered their firstborn at her altar. This is the goddess Disney turned into a redheaded teenager.
        </p>
        <div class="sw-scripture-block">
          <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; The Historical Record</p>
          <p>The first mermaid was not rescued from the sea by a prince. She was a goddess who demanded human sacrifice from the shore.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="sw-section-heading" style="font-size:0.95rem;">Her Myth of Origin</p>
        <p>
          According to the legend preserved by Diodorus Siculus, Atargatis fell in love with a mortal, bore a daughter (Semiramis), and then threw herself into a lake out of shame. The gods transformed her — her lower body became that of a fish, her upper body remained a woman. The daughter she bore, Semiramis, grew up to become the queen of Babylon in the post-flood world and is the original "Queen of Heaven" that Jeremiah would later condemn. The mermaid is the mother of Babylonian idolatry.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── FISH-GOD FAMILY TREE ── -->
    <section class="sw-section">
      <div class="sw-prose">
        <p class="sw-section-heading">The Fish-God Family Tree</p>
        <p>
          Atargatis was never worshipped alone. She was consistently paired with a male consort — a sun god — and their union represented sun and water coming together to produce life. This water-goddess + sun-god pattern is the beating heart of pagan fertility religion, and it repeats across every culture that inherited it from Babel.
        </p>
        <ul class="sw-list">
          <li><strong>Atargatis + Hadad (Syria)</strong> — Fish-goddess paired with the storm-and-sun god. Their union produced the annual harvest.</li>
          <li><strong>Dagon (Philistia)</strong> — The fish-god mentioned in Judges 16:23 and 1 Samuel 5. When the Philistines placed the Ark in Dagon's temple, he fell on his face before it and was broken to pieces.</li>
          <li><strong>Oannes (Babylon)</strong> — The fish-man who rose from the Persian Gulf each morning to teach mankind. His priests wore fish-head mitres — the same mitre the Pope wears today.</li>
          <li><strong>Ea / Enki (Sumer)</strong> — One of the oldest deities in the Mesopotamian pantheon, often depicted as a half-fish figure.</li>
          <li><strong>Nommo (West Africa / Dogon)</strong> — Amphibious ancestor gods said to have descended from the sky to teach humanity. Identical in function to Oannes.</li>
          <li><strong>Melusine (Medieval Europe)</strong> — The twin-tailed mermaid passed down through secret societies and alchemical traditions. She is the figure at the center of the Starbucks logo.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── QUEEN OF HEAVEN ── -->
    <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
      <div class="sw-prose">
        <p class="sw-section-heading">The Queen of Heaven Connection</p>
        <p>
          Scripture names a specific deity Yahuah hates above nearly any other: the Queen of Heaven. She is mentioned by Jeremiah five times, and the context every time is Yahuah's fury at His people for worshipping her.
        </p>
        <div class="sw-scripture-block">
          <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Jeremiah 7:18</p>
          <p>"The children gather wood, and the fathers kindle the fire, and the women knead their dough, to make cakes to the queen of heaven, and to pour out drink offerings unto other gods, that they may provoke Me to anger."</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          This Queen of Heaven is not a single figure with a single name. She is the same goddess worn under different masks: Atargatis in Syria, Astarte in Canaan, Ashtoreth in Phoenicia, Ishtar in Babylon, Isis in Egypt, Aphrodite in Greece, Venus in Rome, and Semiramis in the founding myths. Consistently a fertility goddess, consistently tied to water, consistently paired with a sun god, and consistently portrayed with fish, dove, or star imagery. The mermaid is one of her faces.
        </p>
        <p class="sw-section-heading" style="font-size:0.95rem;">The Twin Tails and the Split Identity</p>
        <p>
          Look carefully at older mermaid imagery — especially medieval and renaissance depictions, and the original Starbucks logo. The classic mermaid is twin-tailed. This is the Melusine figure, and the twin tails held in her hands carry occult significance well documented in the history of heraldry and alchemy.
        </p>
        <p>
          Disney softened this. The animated Little Mermaid has a single tail, a sweet voice, and a redemption arc. But the symbol retains its lineage whether or not the audience recognizes it. A sanitized idol is still an idol.
        </p>
        <div class="sw-scripture-block">
          <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; The Pattern</p>
          <p>The Adversary does not need new material. He only needs new packaging.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── SCRIPTURE ON FISH IDOLS ── -->
    <section class="sw-section">
      <div class="sw-prose">
        <p class="sw-section-heading">How Yahuah Addressed Fish-Idols Directly</p>
        <p>
          The second commandment was not general. It was surgical.
        </p>
        <div class="sw-scripture-block">
          <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Exodus 20:4–5</p>
          <p>"Thou shalt not make unto thee any graven image, or any likeness of any thing that is in heaven above, or that is in the earth beneath, or <strong>that is in the water under the earth</strong>: thou shalt not bow down thyself to them, nor serve them..."</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          "Or that is in the water under the earth" — Yahuah named the exact category the mermaid belongs to. The nations around Israel worshipped water-creature hybrids, and He drew the line specifically to include them. To make an image of a half-human, half-fish being for any devotional purpose is to violate the second commandment exactly as it was written.
        </p>
        <p>
          And lest anyone argue that a Disney cartoon is not worship — ask whether children sing to these figures, dress up as them, write them into bedtime prayers, and organize their imaginative world around them. Ask whether the parents who bring them into the home would have recognized what they were doing if the character had been honestly labeled "Atargatis" instead of "Ariel."
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── DISNEY VERSION ── -->
    <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
      <div class="sw-prose">
        <p class="sw-section-heading">The Disney Version: What the Film Actually Does</p>
        <p>
          The 1989 film sanitizes the myth in every direction that matters to parents — and preserves every element that matters to the worship system:
        </p>
        <ul class="sw-list">
          <li><strong>Ariel is a princess of an undersea kingdom.</strong> Atargatis was queen of an undersea pantheon. Rank preserved.</li>
          <li><strong>Ariel rebels against her father.</strong> The mermaid figure has always been tied to feminine defiance of patriarchal order — a theme that runs through every fertility cult.</li>
          <li><strong>Ariel trades her voice for legs through a sea-witch's spell.</strong> A transformation narrative lifted directly from Atargatis in reverse, accomplished through witchcraft — which Scripture is unambiguous about (Exodus 22:18, Deuteronomy 18:10–12).</li>
          <li><strong>Ariel's goal is the love of a prince.</strong> The fertility-cult marriage narrative preserved: the goddess-figure seeks the mortal consort, the sun-prince, the union that produces the harvest.</li>
          <li><strong>The climax features storm, sea, ritual transformation, and a trident.</strong> All elements lifted from sea-deity worship.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The film is not neutral. It is a fertility myth with a pop soundtrack, teaching children that defying their fathers and pursuing romantic love through witchcraft are noble impulses.
        </p>
        <p class="sw-section-heading">Starbucks and the Everyday Idol</p>
        <p>
          The same Melusine that ran through medieval alchemy now sits on the cup of half the office workers in the western world. The Starbucks logo is a twin-tailed mermaid — the founders have said so publicly. She is encircled by a halo-like ring that functions visually the same way a sun disk functioned on ancient goddess iconography. Earlier versions of the logo showed the twin tails explicitly; later versions cropped the image, but the figure underneath is unchanged.
        </p>
        <p>
          A believer who has rejected the mermaid as a Disney figure must then decide what to do with her on the coffee cup, the tote bag, and the shop window. The answer is the one Yahuah has given from the beginning: come out from among them, and be separate.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── BRINGING IT BACK ── -->
    <section class="sw-section">
      <div class="sw-prose">
        <p class="sw-section-heading">Bringing It Back to the Torah</p>
        <p>
          The good news is not complicated. Messiah Yahushua died and rose so that those buried in these systems could be washed clean of them. Salvation is the door. But the door leads somewhere — and where it leads is back to the instructions Yahuah gave from the beginning.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Torah addresses the mermaid directly. Exodus 20:4 forbids her image. Deuteronomy 12:30–31 forbids inquiring into the ways the nations worshipped their gods. Leviticus 11 calls fish without fins and scales unclean — and the human half of a mermaid has neither. The whole of the Law stands against her.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the believer set free by Yahushua, the response is not fear of a cartoon. It is to recognize what she actually is, remove her from places of honor in the home, and teach children why. The battle is not against Disney. It is against the spiritual system Disney has been advertising for nearly a century.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── SUMMARY ── -->
    <section class="sw-footer-quote">
      <div class="sw-summary-block">
        <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; Summary</p>
        <p class="sw-summary-text">The mermaid is Atargatis, the Syrian fish-goddess, daughter of Babel, mother of Semiramis, sister of every Queen-of-Heaven figure Scripture condemns — and Disney is her latest evangelist.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="sw-quote-text">"Little children, keep yourselves from idols. Amen."</p>
      <p class="sw-quote-ref">— 1 John 5:21</p>
    </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-full -->

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  const btnQuick = document.getElementById('btn-quick');
  const btnFull = document.getElementById('btn-full');
  const btnFullCta = document.getElementById('btn-full-cta');
  const panelQuick = document.getElementById('panel-quick');
  const panelFull = document.getElementById('panel-full');

  function showQuick() {
    panelQuick.style.display = '';
    panelFull.style.display = 'none';
    btnQuick.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnFull.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }
  function showFull() {
    panelFull.style.display = '';
    panelQuick.style.display = 'none';
    btnFull.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnQuick.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }

  btnQuick.addEventListener('click', showQuick);
  btnFull.addEventListener('click', showFull);
  if (btnFullCta) btnFullCta.addEventListener('click', showFull);
</script>

